Minority stress among LGB people: Investigating relations among distal and proximal stressors
Richard P. Douglass1 & Sarah E. Conlin2

# Springer Science+Business Media, LLC, part of Springer Nature 2020
Abstract Research among lesbian, gay, or bisexual (LGB) individuals often distinguishes between distal (e.g., discrimination) and proximal (e.g., expectations of rejection, internalized homophobia, and concealment) stressors. There are few longitudinal studies, however, testing the causal distal-proximal link. The present study examined these proposed associations among a sample of 192 LGB adults. Cross-lagged structural equation modeling revealed that each stressor was stable over 1 month. Also, Time 1 discrimination negatively predicted Time 2 concealment, but Time 1 expectations of rejection positively predicted Time 2 discrimination and concealment. Time 1 concealment positively predicted Time 2 internalized homophobia. Our results suggest the need for further evaluation of the distal-proximal distinction. Practical implications and directions for future research are discussed.
Keywords Discrimination . LGB . Minority stress

People in the United States (U.S.) have reported more support for lesbian, gay, bisexual, or transgender (LGBT) people, but about 37% of Americans still report anti-LGBT prejudice (Brown 2017). After the U.S. presidential election in 2016, LGBT people reported reductions in thriving from 51% to 41% (Gates 2016). Minority stress frameworks (Hatzenbuehler 2009; Meyer 2003) outline how such widespread prejudice against sexual minorities is associated with increased risks for various mental health outcomes (e.g., Brewster et al. 2013; Douglass et al. 2017; Velez and Moradi 2016), but research examining associations among the stressors themselves is limited. This study examines how minority stressors are associated over time.
