has been devoted to testing this proposition through longitudinal research. Distal and proximal stressors may share bidirectional associations (Hatzenbuehler 2009). Discrimination, for example, may be influenced by contextual, personal, and structural factors, suggesting that variables such as expectations of rejection may predict discrimination (Major and O’Brien 2005). Thus, longitudinal data are needed to examine such causal models as cross-sectional data are unable to establish patterns of causality.
Distal Versus Proximal Stressors
Cross-sectional research using minority stress frameworks has positioned proximal stressors as mediators of the links between heterosexist discrimination and mental health outcomes suggesting that discrimination precedes the development of proximal stressors (Brewster et al. 2013; Denton et al. 2014; Douglass et al. 2019; Feinstein et al. 2012). Other research has suggested proximal-distal pathways (e.g., Ragins et al. 2007; Swank et al. 2013) or has positioned distal and proximal stressors on the same level of analysis (e.g., Velez et al. 2013). One study found that a model with distal and proximal stressors on the same level, compared with a mediation model where distal stressors preceded proximal stressors, both had comparable fit indices and no significant differences in fit based on chi-square nested comparisons alone (Mereish and Poteat 2015). Still, determining causality based on any of these cross-sectional studies is difficult.
Some longitudinal studies grounded in minority stress frameworks have examined how distal or proximal stressors are associated with physical or mental health outcomes (e.g., Dyar et al. 2019; Mohr and Sarno 2016; Pachankis et al. 2018; Puckett et al. 2016). These studies are usually focused on how minority stressors are associated with various outcomes and have helped demonstrate the negative effects of sustained minority stressors. Less emphasized, however, are the associations between minority stressors. Focusing on how these stressors influence one another can help to substantiate or modify existing theory, as the notion of reciprocal associations among minority stressors (e.g., Hatzenbuehler 2009; Major and O’Brien 2005) has not been comprehensively tested.
The Present Study
This study examines the distal-proximal stressor distinction proposed in the Minority Stress Model (Meyer 2003) and Psychological Mediation Framework (Hatzenbuehler 2009). We hypothesize that Time 1 discrimination will significantly predict greater levels of Time 2 expectations of rejection, internalized homophobia, and concealment of LGB identity.

There are also two exploratory aims: (1) examine potential bidirectional associations among stressors and (2) explore the temporal stability of minority stressors. This study helps evaluate the directionality of associations between distal and proximal stressors. Cross-lagged structural equation modeling will be used to assess the hypothesized links over 1 month. We chose a period of 1 month to extend on studies that have examined some minority stressors over the course of seven to 10 days (Mohr and Sarno 2016; Swim et al. 2009). A time frame of 1 month will be less sensitive to extreme fluctuations over the course of a week due to a single event while also capturing stressful experiences that could dissipate over a longer time period (Herek et al. 1999; Swim et al. 2009).
Method
Instruments
Discrimination Experiences of discrimination were measured with the 9-item Everyday Discrimination Scale (EDS; Williams et al. 1997), which uses a 6-point Likert scale ranging from never to almost every day. The original EDS specifically evaluated race and ethnicity; thus, we edited the scale instructions for the current study to read “In your day-to-day life, how often do any of the following things happen to you as a result of your sexual orientation?” Participants were asked to consider the events of the past month. Example items include, “You are threatened or harassed,” and “You are called names or insulted.” Williams et al. found an internal consistency reliability estimate of .88 and found evidence of validity as the scale correlated in the expected directions with stress and discrimination. This scale has been used in studies with sexual minority samples and has been found to be reliable and valid among these samples (e.g., Douglass et al. 2017; Frost et al. 2015). In the present study, the internal consistency reliability of scale scores was α = .93 at Time 1 and α = .95 at Time 2.
Expectations of Rejection The 10-item Stigma Consciousness Questionnaire (SCQ; Pinel 1999), which uses a 7-point Likert scale, was used to assess the degree to which participants expected rejection because of being LGB. Item choices ranged from strongly disagree to strongly agree, and sample items include, “I never worry that my behaviors will be viewed as stereotypically LGB,” and “When interacting with people, I feel like they interpret all my behaviors in terms of the fact that I am a LGB person.” The SCQ is often used to measure expectations of rejection among LGB people (e.g., Berghe et al. 2010; Douglass et al. 2017; Lewis et al. 2014). Some scholars have distinguished expectations of rejection from the similar concept of rejection sensitivity by arguing that expectations of rejection is a cognitive process whereas rejection sensitivity also encompasses affective responses (e.g., anxiety; Dyar et al. 2016). This study follows the

