example of previous scholars who employed the SCQ to assess expectations of rejection.
In the original scale construction article for the SCQ, reliability of scale scores was determined with an internal consistency reliability estimation of .81. Validity in the scale’s responses was also demonstrated through correlations in expected directions with measures of stigma and discrimination (Pinel 1999). In the present study, the internal consistency reliability of scale scores was α = .78 at Time 1 and α = .81 at Time 2.
Concealment The 10-item Self-Concealment Scale (SCS; Larson and Chastain 1990) was used to measure the degree to which participants hid being LGB from others. Item choices used a 5-point Likert scale, ranging from strongly disagree to strongly agree. We adapted items to be specific to concealment of LGB identity such as “Being LGB is so private I would lie if anybody asked me about it” instead of “I have a secret that is so private I would lie if anybody asked me about it.” Larson and Chastain found a Cronbach’s alpha of .83 and found evidence of test-retest reliability in the responses over 4-weeks (r = .81). Predictive validity was demonstrated through positive correlations with psychological distress and negative correlations with social support. Factor analyses provided evidence of unidimensionality and showed that responses on the SCS were different than responses on a separate measure of self-disclosure (Larson and Chastain 1990). In the present study, the internal consistency reliability of scale scores was α = .91 at Time 1 and α = .92 at Time 2.

online data collection service Mechanical Turk (MTurk), which is a useful method when sampling hard-to-reach populations, such as LGB people (Smith et al. 2015). MTurk participants have been found to be at least as reliable and diverse as traditional samples (e.g., community; Buhrmester et al. 2011; Goodman et al. 2013).
MTurk workers are compensated for completing Human Intelligence Tasks (HITs). We created a HIT for workers that were at least 18 years old, currently resided in the United States, identified as lesbian, gay, or bisexual, and were willing to participant in a follow-up survey. Workers could click the survey link and were directed to an informed consent page where they could choose to participate. Workers who completed our first survey were contacted 1 month later for the follow-up survey. Participants received $0.30 for each survey.
Of the 484 participants who completed our first survey 22 were removed for incorrectly responding to one of two attention checks (e.g., “Select agree if you are paying attention”). At the end of the survey we also asked participants if their responses should be excluded for any reason—four participants identified as heterosexual and were removed from the sample. After removals, 458 participants were invited to take the second survey and 196 people responded. Of these responses, four participants were removed for failing one of two attention checks resulting in a final sample of 192 people. Demographic information for these participants can be found in Table 1.

Internalized Homophobia Self-stigma that was associated with participants’ sexual orientation was measured using the 5item Revised Internalized Homophobia Scale (IHP-R; Herek et al. 2009), which was developed from the original Internalized Homophobia Scale developed for use with gay men (Martin and Dean 1992). Scale items used a 5-point Likert scale, ranging from strongly disagree to strongly agree, and sample items include, “I wish I weren’t gay/lesbian/bisexual,” and “I feel that being gay/lesbian/bisexual is a personal shortcoming for me.” Herek et al. (2009) found evidence of reliability in the internal consistency estimate of .82, responses were strongly correlated with responses to the original IHP, and test-retest reliability was found in follow-up surveys administered after 1 year (r = .67). Analyses of the IHP-R also showed a similar factor structure to the IHP, which has been found to have good internal consistency reliability and construct validity (Herek et al. 1998). In the present study, the internal consistency reliability of scale scores was α = .89 at Time 1 and α = .88 at Time 2.
