To examine if attrition was associated with age, education, gender, race, social class or the study variables, we used independent samples t tests and chi-squared tests to compare those who completed the survey at just Time 1 to those who completed both surveys. There were not enough participants in each race category to conduct comparisons that would be

adequately powered across all groups, so we created a dummy variable with one group consisting of all non-White participants and another group with White participants. Independent samples t tests showed that those who dropped out were significantly younger (M = 30.23, SD = 8.65 vs. M = 33.73, SD = 10.44, p < .001), and had significantly higher mean scores of discrimination (M = 32.76, SD = 15.80 vs. M = 26.48, SD = 11.09 p < .001) and internalized homophobia (M = 10.41, SD = 5.14 vs. M = 8.77, SD = 4.31 p < .001). There were no significant differences regarding expectations of rejection (p = .526), concealment (p = .138), gender (p = .203), education (p = .148), and social class (p = .752), but more non-white participants dropped out of the study (χ2(1) = 6.10, p = .013). The significantly higher levels of discrimination and internalized homophobia are in line was past research suggesting higher levels of distress contributes to greater levels of attrition (Gustavson et al. 2012).
We also examined group differences between LGB people on the four minority stressors measured at Time 1. Bisexual participants reported significantly lower levels of expectations of rejection (M = 36.97, SD = 9.26) when compared with lesbian (M = 43.07, SD = 7.72, p = .001) and gay (M = 42.44, SD = 9.72, p = .002) participants. Bisexual participants reported significantly greater levels of concealment than lesbian participants (M = 23.08, SD = 9.15 vs. M = 18.82, SD = 8.07, p = .037) and significantly lower levels of discrimination than gay participants (M = 16.07, SD = 7.94 vs. M = 20.40, SD = 8.32, p = .005). There were no significant group differences on scores of internalized homophobia (p = .754). Given the significant differences related to age and race above, and these significant differences regarding specific sexual orientation identity, we conducted all analyses with age, race, and sexual orientation included as covariates.
Missing Data
At Time 1 one participant was missing two data points and 10 participants were missing one data point. At Time 2 nine participants were missing one data point. To see if missingness was systematically associated with age, gender, or any of the study variables, we created a dummy-coded variable to compare participants with and without missing data at each time point and conducted an independent samples t test (Tabachnick and Fidell 2013). The missing and non-missing groups were not significantly different on any of the variables at either time point (p > .05). To address these missing data we used full information maximum likelihood estimation (FIML), which uses all available data to generate estimates with added error to produce unbiased estimates. FIML is considered superior to other methods of handling missing data such as listwise deletion and mean substitution, which tend to produce biased estimates (Tabachnick and Fidell 2013).

