Model Testing
We used SEM in AMOS (Arbuckle 2014) to evaluate our models. To minimize the likelihood of Type I and Type II error, we selected the following fit indices: chi-square (χ2), the Comparative Fit Index (CFI), the Tucker-Lewis Index (TLI) and the Root Mean Square Error of Approximation (RMSEA; Hu and Bentler 1999). A significant χ2 can indicate a poor fitting model, but this test is often significant in larger samples (Tabachnick and Fidell 2013). Criteria for the CFI, TLI, and RMSEA have ranged from less conservative (CFI & TLI ≥ .90; RMSEA ≤ .10) to more conservative (CFI & TLI ≥ .95; RMSEA ≤ .08; Hu and Bentler 1999; Weston and Gore 2006).
Using parcels instead of item-level data when conducting latent variable SEM results in better model fit, less biased estimates, increased reliability, and more precise parameter estimates (Bandalos 2002). The five items that measured internalized homophobia were used as the indicators for the latent construct at both time points. Discrimination, expectations of rejection, and concealment, however, were comprised of more than five items. To maximize equality of factor loadings, we created three parcels each to use as indicators for these latent variables (Little 2013). We created parcels by using exploratory factor analysis on each measure and assigned items to parcels in countervailing order according to the size of the factor loading to ensure they would have approximately equivalent factor loadings (Weston and Gore 2006). We used the same items at both time points to create parcels.
Cross-lagged models consist of two types of paths: autoregressive and cross-lagged. Autoregressive paths are the relation of a variable to itself at subsequent time points (e.g., path from discrimination at Time 1 to itself at Time 2) and represent the stability of a variable. Cross-lagged paths represent the effect of one variable to a different variable over

time (e.g., the effect of Time 1 discrimination on Time 2 concealment). These paths are estimated while controlling for one another whereas a bivariate correlation fails to account for other influences. Cross-lagged panel models allowed us to garner a sense of how minority stressors were associated over time (Kline 2016).
Because we tested models with two time points it was necessary to control for correlations of the variables at Time 1, the covariances at Time 2, and the cross-wave error terms of the same observed indicators (Cole and Maxwell 2003). We also ensured that our model satisfied assumptions of configural and weak factorial invariance. Configural invariance constrains the constructs to be in the same configurations at each time point and was tested with our measurement model. To test weak factorial invariance we constrained factor loadings to be equivalent across time and compared fit indices to the configural model to determine if model fit declined. This examination of invariance is an essential pre-condition in longitudinal designs (Chan 1998; Widaman et al. 2010).
Measurement Model
The measurement model – which was analogous to the configural model – had good fit to the data, χ2 (368) = 637.72, p < .001, CFI = .95, TLI = .93, and RMSEA = .06, 90% CI [.05, .07]. All latent variable indicators loaded onto their respective factors at .63 or higher. This model was compared with the weak factorial invariance model, which also had good fit to the data χ2 (378) = 653.79, p < .001, CFI = .94, TLI = .93, and RMSEA = .06, 90% CI [.05, .07]. All indicators loaded onto their respective factors at .65 or higher. This model produced a non-significant change in fit χ2 (10) = 16.07, p = .098. Thus, the factor structures of the study constructs were consistent across time.

