Structural Models
Our first structural model was a baseline model where each Time 1 variable only predicted its associated Time 2 variable. This model had good fit to the data, χ2 (390) = 675.87, p < .001, CFI = .94, TLI = .93, and RMSEA = .06, 90% CI [.05, .07]. Each Time 1 variable significantly predicted itself at Time 2 with standardized estimates as follows: discrimination (β = .78, SE = .05, p < .001), expectations of rejection (β = .73, SE = .06, p < .001), internalized homophobia (β = .80, SE = .04, p < .001), and concealment (β = .80, SE = .05, p < .001). Next, we tested a reciprocal model that included paths from the baseline model along with paths from each of the variables at Time 1 to the other variables at Time 2. This model also had good fit to the data χ2 (378) = 653.29, p < .001, CFI = .94, TLI = .93, and RMSEA = .06, 90% CI [.05, .07] and was a significant improvement compared with the baseline model Δχ2 (12) = 22.58, p = .032. As seen in Fig. 1, Time 1 discrimination significantly and negatively predicted Time 2 concealment (p = .026). Time 1 expectations of rejection significantly and positively predicted Time 2 discrimination (p = .034) and concealment (p = .033). Lastly, Time 1 concealment significantly and positively predicted Time 2 internalized homophobia (p = .048). Because deleting non-significant paths would be based on the specific variation within our sample, we did not run a final trimmed model (Goodboy and Kline 2017). Factor loadings and covariances for this final model can be found in Tables 3 and 4.
Discussion
In the Minority Stress Model (Meyer 2003) and Psychological Mediation Framework (Hatzenbuehler 2009) distal stressors (e.g., heterosexist discrimination) are positioned as predictors of proximal stressors (e.g., expectations of rejection, internalized homophobia, and concealment of LGB identity). None of our hypotheses were supported as Time 1 discrimination was only associated with Time 2 sexual orientation concealment but in the direction opposite our hypothesis. Greater scores of Time 1 discrimination were associated with lower Time 2 concealment scores. Although contrary to the Minority Stress Model, this finding aligns with research that has found heterosexist discrimination to predict greater levels of disclosure (or less concealment; Ragins et al. 2007). Also, identity disclosure occurs along a continuum (e.g., partial versus full disclosure) and can have positive and negative outcomes (Ragins 2008). For people already experiencing heterosexist discrimination concealing one’s LGB identity may no longer serve the role of inhibiting discrimination, at which point disclosure may contribute to positive outcomes such as increased social connection, support, and well-being (Pachankis 2007; Ragins 2008).

The use of cross-lagged panel models allowed us to examine the first exploratory aim of examining reciprocal relations among minority stressors. Time 1 expectations of rejection was significantly and positively associated with Time 2 discrimination. Expectations of rejection was the only proximal variable to be significantly associated with discrimination at Time 2, which suggests that expectations of rejection may precede discrimination. This finding aligns with the idea that contextual, personal, and structural factors likely interact to influence perceptions of discrimination (Major and O’Brien 2005). Both the Minority Stress Model (Meyer 2003) and Psyhcological Mediation Framework (Hatzenbuehler 2009) acknowledge the role of structural forces. When LGB people are expecting rejection based on their sexual orientation, likely in situations where contextual or structural factors have created unwelcome environments (e.g., states that still have discriminatory laws based on sexual orientation), they may be more likely to experience discriminatory events.
Time 1 expectations of rejection was also significantly associated with greater Time 2 concealment, which may serve a protective function (Collins and Zimmerman 1983). When expectations of rejection are high concealment of one’s LGB status may be used to prevent potential negative consequences. Also regarding concealment, Time 1 concealment was positively associated with Time 2 internalized homophobia (Bruce et al. 2015). Concealment may have the potential to strengthen internal homophobic attitudes. The notion that concealment of a stigmatized identity contributes to negative views of self has been found across many stigmatized groups such as racial and ethnic minorities, the unemployed, those with mental illnesses, and sexual minorities (Pachankis 2007).
The autogregressive paths in our models allowed us to examine the second exploratory aim of assessing the stability of our measures over 1 month. All the paths evidenced a great deal of stability. This finding suggests that, among our sample, the experience of both distal and proximal stressors was consistent over 1 month. The stability of these paths may have been the result of the time frame of the study. Greater variability may be present in studies using shorter or longer assessment windows.
Practical Implications
Working collaboratively with LGB clients may help both clients and practitioners to understand the sociocultural contexts that contribute to the development and experience of minority stressors. Identifying structural elements that may be influencing expectations of rejection may help to promote acceptance and empowerment. This approach mirrors multiculturalfeminist therapies, which move beyond the individual and toward consideration of influential external forces. Because structural factors have the potential to influence minority stressors, we recommend that practitioners take on advocacy

