We found that concealment predicted future internalized homophobia, or negative self-directed attitudes regarding one’s sexual orientation. Practitioners may wish to explore reasons contributing to concealment and discuss both potential benefits (e.g., serving as a protective function; Collins and Zimmerman 1983) and consequences that can result from sexual orientation concealment (e.g., increased internalized homophobia). These conversations need to be considerate of each client’s unique social and cultural context. It may be helpful to also discuss the potential benefits and consequences of identity disclosure (e.g., increased social connection and support; Collins and Zimmerman 1983; Ragins 2008) and the idea that disclosure occurs along a continuum (Ragins 2008). Concealment and disclosure may be dynamic, situation-dependent processes with the potential for both

