Limitations and Future Directions
A major strength of this study is the examination of the relations between distal and proximal stressors across two time points. Although this study alone cannot establish patterns of causality, our findings can help to guide future research. The limitations of this study provide directions for future research using minority stress models. First, because we only collected responses at two time points, we were unable to examine indirect effects (Cole and Maxwell 2003). Studies with at least three measurement points would allow for a more comprehensive examination of minority stress frameworks consisting of the distal and proximal stressors along with mental health outcomes. We did not examine physical or mental health outcomes because we first sought to examine how the relations between distal and proximal stressors manifested. More comprehensive studies of stressors and outcomes over more time points will also allow for an examination of non-linear trajectories, which may have been missed due to this study’s design.
In addition to not including physical or mental health outcomes, this study did not assess any sources of resilience. Future research should include potential stress-buffering factors (e.g., social support, community connectedness), which are included in minority stress models (e.g., Hatzenbuehler 2009; Meyer 2003). Incorporating resilience factors will require thoughtful study design because scholars have suggested that studies conducted over longer spans, such as data collected 6 months apart, may allow participants more time to cope with discriminatory experiences (Herek et al. 1999; Swim et al. 2009).

