Another limitation is that approximately 80% of our participants identified as White. This point is especially critical because past research has found that LGB people of color have varying relations among stigma, internalized homophobia, and outness when compared with White LGB individuals (Moradi et al. 2010). Researchers should also attempt to recruit and retain participants that may be experiencing greater levels of minority stress than typically reported because participants who dropped out of this study reported greater levels of discrimination and internalized homophobia. To inform work and interventions with LGB people experiencing varying levels of minority stress, it is necessary to recruit participants with a range of experiences. Similarly, future studies should incorporate the experiences of gender minorities. Although the Minority Stress Model (Meyer 2003) was originally intended to explain the experiences of sexual minorities, the model has since been expanded to address the unique experiences of people with varying gender identities (Hendricks and Testa 2012). Our sample consisted of some individuals of diverse gender identities, but our measures only captured the experiences of sexual versus gender minority stress.
Lastly, future research should attempt to replicate these findings using measures of heterosexist discrimination and sexual orientation concealment developed specifically for the experiences of sexual minorities. Our measure of discrimination was adapted from a measure developed to assess discrimination based on race/ethnicity, and our concealment measure originally assessed a “secret” that was not necessarily related to sexual orientation. These measures may not have fully captured the discrimination experiences of LGB people. Although the bivariate associations of our minority stressors were similar to past minority stress research it’s possible the cross-lagged results may differ if other measures are used.
Conclusion
Our findings highlight that there may be bidirectional relations among distal and proximal stressors as outlined in the Psychological Mediation Framework (Hatzenbuehler 2009). Within minority stress frameworks variables in crosssectional studies are often linearly positioned despite little empirical data to support such temporal connections. Until future research tests the replicability of our findings, and generalizability to other stressors, researchers should carefully consider the implied causal positioning of stressors described in the Minority Stress Model (Meyer 2003). The results of this study add to the growing call for minority stress frameworks to undergo longitudinal examination, which would allow scholars to speak more confidently about theorized temporal relations. We also hope these findings inform clinical work with LGB clients by underscoring the need to consider the

nuanced relations that exist among minority stressors instead of assuming that some experiences necessarily contribute to others.
